American Sign Language Teacher Certification
Many high school students take a year or two of Spanish as an elective class; others take French. Some take German or Japanese, when teachers are available at their school; while still others opt for American Sign Language.
American Sign Language? As a foreign language? Indeed! Contrary to popular belief, American Sign Language (ASL) is not a form of English. Rather, it is a fully developed and independent language, spoken by many people across the nation‚Äîboth deaf and hearing. Unfortunately, too many schools lack a teacher who can teach it. This is where a certified ASL teacher can make a huge difference in the culture of a school‚Äîand in the lives of students who need them.
